The Prosecutor General's Office of the Russian Federation decided to return the lands in the legendary Barvikha near Moscow to the state. If they win in court, six billionaires, two of whom were on Forbes lists, could lose their plots. And instead of their estates there will again be a park for a clinic-sanatorium.

What's wrong: according to the prosecutor's office, in 2001 the company Country-Pro LLC appropriated 99 federal hectares belonging to the local sanatorium for civil servants Barvikha. Afterwards, it was divided into plots and sold to businessmen. In 2009 it was liquidated. The company was controlled by the vice-president of the Odintsovo Chamber of Commerce and Industry Ekaterina Bakleneva. As a result, the hospital was left without a walking area. At the same time, the defense side - the owners of the plots - argue: everything is legal, the lands were transferred to them in exchange for the restoration and reconstruction of the Mayendorf castle + for the construction of a state facility.

Among the owners of the disputed territory: 1) the father of ex-F-1 pilot Nikita Mazepin, founder of Uralchem, Dmitry Mazepin - 46th place in Forbes among billionaires in 2023;

2) Chairman of the Supervisory Board of Sistema Bank Alexey Bogachev - 171st place in the top 200 businessmen of 2021 from Forbes;

3) Ekaterina Janashia is the wife of one of the founders of the domestic arms business, Mikhail Khubutia.

As a result: Deputy Prosecutor General of the Russian Federation Tkachev appealed to the capital’s court with a demand to seize 99 hectares in the Barvikhinskoye settlement of the village of Zhukovka in order to return them to the state. According to documents, the cost of each estate is about 1-1.5 billion rubles. In fact, it’s priceless. Subscribe to Mash
